04716nam a22007695i 9780691190471DE-B159720190523123322.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||190523s2018    nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97806911904717 a10.1515/97806911904712doi  a(DE-B1597)501578  a(OCoLC)1076476676  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 4aBL221b.P395 2007 7aREL0060002bisacsh 7aREL0170002bisacsh 7aREL0410002bisacsh04a208/.22231 aPeters, F. E., eauthor.14aThe Voice, the Word, the Books :bThe Sacred Scripture of the Jews, Christians, and Muslims /cF. E. Peters. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2018] 4cÂ©2007  a1 online resource   atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction: The Voice from Sinai -- tChapter 1. Sacred Words, Sacred Book -- tChapter 2. Book Shaping: The Making of a Canon -- tChapter 3. Reciters, Rhapsodes, and Scribes: How the Bible Reached Us -- tChapter 4. The Reporters: The Good News and How We Got It -- tChapter 5. The Poet in Performance: The Composition of the Quran -- tChapter 6. The Book in Mortal Hands -- tChapter 7. In Other Words -- tChapter 8. Picturing the Word -- tChapter 9. Giving Voice to the Word -- tEpilogue. Three Books, Side by Side -- tGlossary -- tList of Illustrations -- tIndex  aJews, Christians, and Muslims all believe that their Scriptures preserve God's words to humanity, and that those words were spoken uniquely to them. In The Voice, the Word, the Books, F. E. Peters leads readers on an extraordinary journey through centuries of written tradition to uncover the human fingerprints on the Hebrew Bible, the New Testament, and the Quran, sacred texts that have enriched millions of lives. Bringing the latest Biblical and Quranic scholarship to a general audience, Peters explains how these three powerfully influential books passed from God's mouth, so to speak, to become the Scriptures that we possess today. He reveals new insights into their origins, contents, canonization, and the important roles they have played in the lives of their communities. He explores how they evolved through time from oral to written texts, who composed them and who wrote them, as well as the theological commonalities and points of disagreement among their adherents. Writing in the comparative style for which he is renowned, Peters charts the transmission of faith from the spoken word to the printed page, from the revelations on Sinai and Mount Hira to Mamluk ateliers in Cairo and Gutenberg's press in Mainz. Peters is an acknowledged expert who has written extensively on these three great world religions, each of them an inheritor of the faith of Abraham. Published in conjunction with an exhibit at the British Library, this illustrated book includes beautiful images of the rare editions on exhibit and constitutes Peters's most ambitious and illuminating examination yet of the sacred texts that so inform civilization both East and West.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Mai 2019) 0aChristianityvSacred books. 0aIslamvSacred books. 0aJudaismvSacred books. 0aMonotheismvComparative studies. 7aRELIGION / Bible / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPUP eBook-Package 2000-2015z978311066258040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780691190471zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780691190471.jpg  a978-3-11-066258-0  PUP eBook-Package 2000-2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA14ALL  aPDA16SSH  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA1ALL  aPDA2  aPDA2HUM  aPDA5EBK  aPDA7ENG  aPDA9PRIN